Files written:

- **`.lathe/goal.md`** — The goal-setter's behavioral doc. Four stakeholders: lathe users (the loop must produce genuine value, not theater), contributors (clean code, reliable CI), init users (alignment summary must feel project-specific), and the future stakeholder sim (architectural decisions should not close off that direction). Tensions are drawn from what's actually visible in the code and docs — particularly the current-model-vs-sim tension and the meta-prompt-vs-engine tension. No layer ladder.

- **`.lathe/skills/architecture.md`** — The two-prompt-layer model, file map, key invariants, session state layout, template placeholders, build and CI details.

- **`.lathe/skills/testing.md`** — Test runner commands, the three test files, `setupTestState` helper, what is and isn't covered (the meta-prompts have no tests — that's noted explicitly), Linux vs. macOS divergence.

- **`.lathe/skills/domains.md`** — Domain map covering Go/stdlib, the LLM CLI interface, GitHub/gh CLI, agent prompt design, git, and shell/OS. Common misattributions included — so the goal-setter and builder don't try to fix meta-prompt bugs in engine code.

- **`.lathe/alignment-summary.md`** — Stakeholders, tensions, and what could be wrong. The last section flags the lathe-on-lathe concern from project memory — whether this init is experimental and the goal-setter should be conservative.
